Architecture plan for Issue #27: Apply a dark theme to the calculator UI

Project shape and tech stack
- React 19 + TypeScript single-page calculator app built with Vite.
- Styling is Tailwind utility classes in JSX plus global Tailwind layers in src/styles.css.
- No backend, auth, database, or email capability is required for this issue.
- Validation should use npm run format:check, npm run lint, npm test, and npm run build; Playwright e2e can be run if browser dependencies are available.

Module structure and file organization
- src/App.tsx: top-level page shell and background. Dark theme work should update the full-page background and preserve centered layout.
- src/features/calculator/Calculator.tsx: calculator shell, heading, mode toggle, and mode toggle button styles. State/reducer/evaluator logic should remain unchanged.
- src/components/CalcButton.tsx: reusable button primitive. Update base, focus, disabled, active-ring, and variant classes for digit/operator/function/control/equals buttons.
- src/components/Display.tsx: display panel and text colors. Preserve aria-labels, aria-live behavior, error role, and monospace numeric layout.
- src/features/calculator/keypads/*: keypad structure and aria labels should not need changes unless a class from CalcButton is insufficient.
- src/styles.css: global base colors can be adjusted only if needed; prefer component-level Tailwind classes for the requested scope.

Shared types and contracts
- Existing CalcButtonVariant, CalcButtonSize, CalculatorMode, CalculatorState, and CalculatorAction types remain sufficient.
- No new shared types are expected for a visual theme change.
- The evaluateExpression engine and tests under src/engine are unaffected and should not be modified.

Issue dependency plan
- There is only one issue in this batch, so there are no cross-issue dependencies.
- The implementation is isolated to UI styling and should not alter calculator behavior, keyboard shortcuts, error messages, or evaluator semantics.

Key design decisions
- Use a cohesive dark palette with accessible contrast across page, shell, toggles, buttons, and display.
- Keep high-visibility focus rings for keyboard accessibility.
- Maintain distinct semantic button colors: digits neutral dark, operators primary/accent, functions secondary, controls warning/destructive, equals success.
- Preserve layout dimensions and responsive behavior so existing e2e selectors and accessible names continue to pass.
- Avoid introducing a theme system unless needed; the issue asks for applying a dark theme, not user-selectable themes.
